# 🔐 Inconsistent Security Controls

## Lab Overview

This lab demonstrates how inconsistent implementation of security controls can result in privilege escalation.

The application restricts registration to users with an internal company email domain. However, the same restriction is not consistently enforced when users later update their account details.

---

## Objective

Gain access to the administrator panel and delete the target user.

---

## Vulnerability Type

- Access Control
- Privilege Escalation
- Business Logic Flaw

---

## Reconnaissance

During registration, the application displayed the following requirement:

> If you work for DontWannaCry, please use your @dontwannacry.com email address.

This indicates that internal users are granted additional privileges based on their email domain.

---

## Step 1 – Register a New Account

Created a normal user account using an attacker-controlled email address.

```text
Username: test1
Email: attacker@exploit-server.net
Password: ********
```

The application sent an email verification link.

---

## Step 2 – Verify Account

Opened the exploit server mailbox and clicked the account verification link.

The account was successfully activated.

---

## Step 3 – Access Account Settings

After logging in, navigated to:

```text
My Account
```

Observed an option to update the registered email address.

---

## Step 4 – Change Email Domain

Modified the email address from:

```text
attacker@exploit-server.net
```

to

```text
test@dontwannacry.com
```

The application accepted the change without validating whether the user should be allowed to use the internal company domain.

---

## Step 5 – Privilege Escalation

After updating the email address, a new option appeared:

```text
Admin Panel
```

This confirmed that administrative access was being granted solely based on the email domain.

---

## Step 6 – Access Admin Panel

Navigated to:

```text
/ admin
```

Successfully gained administrator privileges.

---

## Step 7 – Delete Target User

Deleted the target user:

```text
carlos
```

Lab solved successfully.

---

## Root Cause

The application enforced email-domain restrictions during registration but failed to apply the same validation when users updated their email addresses.

This inconsistency allowed privilege escalation.

---

## Impact

Such vulnerabilities can lead to:

- Unauthorized administrative access
- Privilege escalation
- Account compromise
- Data manipulation
- User deletion
- Business logic abuse

---

## Remediation

- Apply security controls consistently across all workflows.
- Revalidate sensitive attributes whenever they are modified.
- Implement centralized authorization logic.
- Never rely solely on user-controlled attributes for privilege decisions.

---

## Key Takeaway

Security controls are only effective when they are enforced consistently throughout the application.

A single validation gap can become a complete privilege escalation path.

---

